Nice. This quick and dirty trick has been in my .bashrc forever and I still use it:<p><pre><code>    function md(){
        pwd > /tmp/md_tmp

    function gomd(){
        cd `cat /tmp/md_tmp`
</code></pre>
so `md` marks the current directory and `gomd`go to the marked directory. Unlike bash builtins like pushd and popd, it uses the file system to store the marked directory so you  can pop up a new terminal and just do gomd. (you can&#x27;t with pushd/popd since the bash processes of the old and the new terminal are not related)<p>Edit: I see that your script uses links, I&#x27;ll check this out.
